rComments: Avoid this professor if you can, very difficult grader, pretty rude and unforgiving.

I walked in thinking he will be a great prof given his good reviews but he is awful and rude to students. His grading and criteria for assignments are vague and he is nothing like the good ratings say he is. He records his lectures but even that does not help. He is condescending and doesn't care if students fail. One of the worst professors.

These other reviews must have been written by Professor Pendakur himself! In fact, the "warm and fuzzy" statement was said by him in class last week. Professor Pendakur is far from patient; he is extremely condescending when you ask a question. He does not care at all as he's said himself multiple times, and his expectations are not clear.
Great professor. No surprises in his exams or assignments. Very patient when you ask a question.

One of the most patient profs I've ever had. If you don't understand something, he'll explain it until you do without getting frustrated or annoyed. Has loads of extra office hours and goes well out of his way to help you with materials and assignments. Ultra cynical and super funny. Good dude, but not in the warm fuzzy type of way.

Very helpful/ funny very knowledgeable. Gives extra classes to those that don't have a background in stats. Just be prepared to come to early office hours (8 am +). Highly recommended. The best in the department for sure.

Pendakur is my favourite type of prof: insightful, a tad cynical, accomplished, unpretentious AND he knows how to teach. He has high but not unreasonable expectations. His course is designed to get students to think critically and create their own informed personal opinions. You probably won't pass the class if you're really lazy or don't show up.
Very interesting and thought provoking teacher. I definately suggest taking this class if you are interested in urban issues :)
